1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:28,468
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble,

2
00:00:28,786 --> 00:00:35,014
and fully self-awakened.

3
00:00:35,194 --> 00:00:40,140
So this evening, I thought to tackle this business of need, sufficiency and greed.

4
00:00:41,523 --> 00:00:56,902
As you know, in the UK here, well, I think it's all over the world, but in Europe and the UK, we've got these huge national debts and in the UK, it's made worse by the wonderful Brexit deal that was made.

5
00:00:57,136 --> 00:01:02,183
And everybody's predicting high inflation and a downturn.

6
00:01:03,887 --> 00:01:08,515
So this is frightening, you know, because you lose your savings.

7
00:01:09,034 --> 00:01:10,236
You might lose your work.

8
00:01:10,837 --> 00:01:13,602
It can all be very upsetting.

9
00:01:14,825 --> 00:01:22,957
So I just thought, well, what we need to do is undermine the fear and anxiety by asking ourselves, what do we actually need?

10
00:01:23,512 --> 00:01:34,221
So what I want to do is just explain to you, and most of you won't know, what the rules for the monks are when it comes to their physical well-being.

11
00:01:36,144 --> 00:01:37,626
So the first one is shelter.

12
00:01:38,525 --> 00:01:50,498
So in the discourse on how to establish right mindfulness, the Buddha said that we should be happy with the wilderness, a root of a tree or an empty hut.

13
00:01:52,451 --> 00:01:54,936
Now, those reflect the three seasons.

14
00:01:55,617 --> 00:01:58,180
So you want a hut when it rains, in the rainy season.

15
00:01:58,740 --> 00:02:00,644
You want a tree in the hot season.

16
00:02:01,305 --> 00:02:06,192
And in the cool season, well, you can sleep anywhere and do your meditation anywhere.

17
00:02:06,212 --> 00:02:21,936
And in fact, if I remember rightly, when the Buddha settled down to his meditation, which brought about the liberation, the enlightenment, near a place called Uruvila, which is now, of course, Bodh Gaya,

18
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:27,388
It sounds as though it was a cool season, which makes a lot of sense.

19
00:02:27,427 --> 00:02:30,252
If you're going to make a big effort, you want it to be cool.

20
00:02:32,435 --> 00:02:42,788
And so when we look around our houses, our flats or whatever we're living, you can ask yourself, well, what do you actually need, right?

21
00:02:43,469 --> 00:02:48,818
Not what you want or even what is sufficient, but what do you actually need?

22
00:02:49,455 --> 00:02:54,302
So I'm thinking of things like heating.

23
00:02:55,243 --> 00:03:06,860
So there was a little article where a man had explained that when he called up the electrical company, they told him, well, to reduce heating, just heat one room.

24
00:03:07,622 --> 00:03:09,765
And he seemed to be quite upset by that.

25
00:03:10,265 --> 00:03:13,330
He had a great big, he sounded as though he lived on his own.

26
00:03:13,431 --> 00:03:16,155
I mean, he had a family, that's different, of course.

27
00:03:16,134 --> 00:03:22,144
But living on his own in a house, he was quite upset that he had now reduced his heating to one room.

28
00:03:22,805 --> 00:03:28,212
Well, I mean, if you think about what you actually need, it probably is just the room you're generally living in.

29
00:03:30,316 --> 00:03:33,420
So I met somebody at Gaia House when I was teaching there.

30
00:03:33,681 --> 00:03:34,983
I've known him for a long time.

31
00:03:35,584 --> 00:03:41,231
And he says during winter, he lives at 12 degrees centigrade.

32
00:03:42,307 --> 00:03:47,254
You'd have to, if you really want to know how he does it, I can always put you in touch with him.

33
00:03:47,876 --> 00:03:51,300
But that's what he actually gets down to, 12 degrees.

34
00:03:51,341 --> 00:03:56,106
And then he says, if it's under 12, then he starts to lose it.

35
00:03:56,127 --> 00:03:59,372
He can feel the body heat really reducing too much.

36
00:04:00,593 --> 00:04:01,675
So that's all he needs.

37
00:04:01,915 --> 00:04:03,657
He needs just 12 degrees.

38
00:04:05,174 --> 00:04:11,121
But of course, we tend to walk around our houses at 25 degrees.

39
00:04:11,520 --> 00:04:16,326
In the middle of winter, you find people wearing just a T-shirt walking around the house.

40
00:04:17,367 --> 00:04:24,375
So again, if the price of gas and all this is going to go up, well, it throws us back on ourselves.

41
00:04:24,396 --> 00:04:27,519
I mean, how much do you actually need?

42
00:04:28,208 --> 00:04:38,966
there was an article for people who are really poor, who are really going to have real problems, that they can buy these rather cheap jackets and pullovers that are heated.

43
00:04:39,468 --> 00:04:52,512
You just stick the plug in and the batteries fill up and then the body armour gives you heat.

44
00:04:54,971 --> 00:05:03,927
So again, it's just a reflection on, you know, I mean, one exercise I was going to suggest at the end was, what would you take with you?

45
00:05:04,088 --> 00:05:06,612
What would you need if you were a refugee?

46
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:12,242
And of course, there are people who are homeless.

47
00:05:12,442 --> 00:05:18,954
I mean, you know, we know that people are living really rough, even in the depths of winter.

48
00:05:19,103 --> 00:05:25,557
So it's not a case of getting to a point where we're like that, but it's a good question to ask.

49
00:05:25,596 --> 00:05:29,665
When it comes to dwelling, what do I actually need?

50
00:05:30,346 --> 00:05:35,036
I mean, I lived for quite some time just in a bedsit.

51
00:05:35,201 --> 00:05:38,185
And it was in the house of my teacher in Birmingham.

52
00:05:38,425 --> 00:05:41,850
And she had prepared this room specifically for a monk.

53
00:05:42,711 --> 00:05:49,360
And it was just, you know, just a bed, a place to sit next to the fire, gas fire.

54
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:58,711
And on one side looking was just a small stove, a fridge, and a little cabinet for

55
00:05:59,468 --> 00:06:28,935
you know for um uh pots and pots and pans and stuff like that i was i was very happy so that's to do with dwelling right what do you actually need now when it comes to food uh the monastic has to go out with his bowl and uh just accept what's given so there were famines in those days and um and often they would have to just make do with whatever was put in the bowl in terms of rice um

56
00:06:31,531 --> 00:06:41,812
The Buddha, well, lay people complained to the Buddha that these monks and nuns were turning up at all times of the day and asking for food and, you know, being quite a nuisance.

57
00:06:42,653 --> 00:06:43,896
So he made a rule.

58
00:06:43,956 --> 00:06:46,079
He said, right, well, from now on,

59
00:06:46,177 --> 00:06:56,434
You have to go out in the early hours or during the morning on alms round and you have to finish eating and everything else by noon.

60
00:06:57,055 --> 00:07:00,920
Well, there was a lot of monks rejected that, you know, they got very upset.

61
00:07:01,302 --> 00:07:04,547
I mean, you know, they would normally have had an evening meal.

62
00:07:05,007 --> 00:07:07,831
They would normally have had three meals a day.

63
00:07:07,812 --> 00:07:09,754
And so there was a bit of a rebellion.

64
00:07:10,276 --> 00:07:16,466
And the Buddha said, look, he said, if you want to belong to this dispensation, then that's what you're going to have to do.

65
00:07:17,266 --> 00:07:20,452
And for the most part, monks try to keep that rule.

66
00:07:21,274 --> 00:07:24,920
So again, it's a case of, well, how much food do you actually need?

67
00:07:25,060 --> 00:07:32,351
And of course, there's a distinction between good food and food which is not so good for the body.

68
00:07:32,584 --> 00:07:36,819
And that's the problem, I think, with people on these food banks.

69
00:07:38,043 --> 00:07:43,422
When you get a shot of a food bank, some of it tends to be all tins, for heaven's sake.

70
00:07:46,961 --> 00:07:55,250
But again, it's just settling down and just thinking to yourself, making up a little menu for yourself, which is really basic.

71
00:07:55,571 --> 00:08:09,925
So now, when I was in India, the regular food for the ordinary worker, the ordinary person, you might say, in North India, was dal, vegetable curry, and a chapati.

72
00:08:10,286 --> 00:08:11,346
And that's what you got every day.

73
00:08:11,567 --> 00:08:15,230
You didn't say, well, I'm going to have a Chinese today.

74
00:08:15,413 --> 00:08:21,081
It was just, you know, dal, vegetable curry, and a chapati.

75
00:08:21,423 --> 00:08:22,944
And that's what you may do with.

76
00:08:24,487 --> 00:08:36,868
Interestingly enough, when they started to recruit men during conscription for the Second World War, they were really taken aback to find that many of the men weren't having three meals a day at all.

77
00:08:37,208 --> 00:08:42,417
They were actually eating really bad and were happy to join the army just to get some decent food, I think.

78
00:08:45,518 --> 00:09:03,341
uh so you know it's like another little exercise you might set yourself a little while anyway is you know to have a day as if you were poor as if you couldn't you know just buy the food you need what would you eat what would be what would sustain you for that day you know

79
00:09:04,250 --> 00:09:15,167
So again, it's just taking away this fear that if we become very poor for one reason or another, that that's not the end of the world.

80
00:09:15,287 --> 00:09:16,128
You just make do.

81
00:09:22,398 --> 00:09:26,023
I mean, I'm old enough to have memories of just after the war.

82
00:09:26,264 --> 00:09:31,692
And I remember going to my aunt's for food.

83
00:09:31,975 --> 00:09:56,058
uh on the toast you see you put the butter on the toast and then you scraped it off and what you were left with was just a sort of a little suggestion and then they did the same with the jam i mean i couldn't believe it i was only a kid i must have been about six or seven you know just looking at this you put a jam on on the bread and then scraped it all off and then stuck it on another piece

84
00:09:57,337 --> 00:09:59,234
All these were considered luxury.

85
00:09:59,537 --> 00:10:02,522
I mean, the food was the bread itself.

86
00:10:05,826 --> 00:10:17,639
When it comes to clothing, again, the Buddha noticed that people were coming away with huge amounts of cloth from the laypeople.

87
00:10:18,279 --> 00:10:27,288
And so he actually set out one night, on a cold night, this would have been the cold season, to actually decide how many robes you actually need.

88
00:10:27,950 --> 00:10:35,057
So in the beginning of the night, he had his lower robe and the top robe, this one here.

89
00:10:35,037 --> 00:11:02,039
and then as the night got colder he needed another robe so he took another road and then towards the end of the night you know the coldest hour is just before dawn he felt he needed one more so he had he he put the last two together right and those are your three robes the lower robe the upper robe and the sangati the one that that you see monks putting over their shoulder and that was it and that was the rule then that's all you could have

90
00:11:02,019 --> 00:11:23,639
um but of course rules are rules and and uh and and you get ways around it by having extra cloth which is a bit cheeky i know but it was just just coming down to what do you actually need and i mean of course we're talking about the the tropics but what do you actually need you know how many coats do you need how many pair of shoes do you need

91
00:11:23,620 --> 00:11:39,755
And it's just drawing ourselves down to that basic need that I think gets rid of a lot of the fear that comes from a loss of wealth, whatever that wealth is, a loss of your job and so on and so forth.

92
00:11:47,043 --> 00:11:53,289
And just as an aside, of course, it does make us more aware of where we're getting our clothes from, you know.

93
00:11:54,028 --> 00:11:57,356
I met somebody and they showed me this.

94
00:11:57,376 --> 00:12:02,027
I was in Shropshire and they showed me this jumper they just bought, you see.

95
00:12:02,347 --> 00:12:05,355
And they said they bought it for so many pounds, I think.

96
00:12:05,722 --> 00:12:07,625
or three or four pounds or something.

97
00:12:08,265 --> 00:12:14,392
And they'd gone to this other shop, probably Marks and Spencer's, and it was a similar jumper, it was 12 pounds, you see.

98
00:12:14,793 --> 00:12:22,441
And when I said to them, yeah, but this is probably made in one of those satanic sweatshops in Bangladesh, it was taken by surprise.

99
00:12:22,682 --> 00:12:24,744
It hadn't even occurred to him to think that way.

100
00:12:28,827 --> 00:12:35,054
Now the final one, so we've done shelter, food,

101
00:12:36,048 --> 00:12:36,589
Clothing.

102
00:12:37,931 --> 00:12:39,072
The final one is medicine.

103
00:12:39,493 --> 00:12:47,664
Now, the Buddha said that we should be contented with fermented cow's urine.

104
00:12:48,566 --> 00:12:50,048
Now, that might come as a big surprise.

105
00:12:50,929 --> 00:12:54,914
But in fact, it's a very well-known Ayurvedic medicine.

106
00:12:55,635 --> 00:12:56,778
It's an antibiotic.

107
00:12:56,798 --> 00:12:59,101
Let me just get it here.

108
00:13:02,706 --> 00:13:04,249
It's an antibiotic.

109
00:13:04,852 --> 00:13:22,361
anti-fungal, and if you take it regularly, it maintains the homeostasis of the body to lower cholesterol, relieve tension, enhance liver function, and slow down aging.

110
00:13:23,244 --> 00:13:30,456
So tomorrow morning, you need to get out there and get your bottle of fermented cow's urine

111
00:13:32,258 --> 00:13:35,105
So that's what we're supposed to be happy with.

112
00:13:35,407 --> 00:13:36,991
Now, frankly, I've never tried it.

113
00:13:37,833 --> 00:13:41,504
So I don't want to say whether it's any good or not.

114
00:13:42,187 --> 00:13:46,740
But it's definitely Ayurvedic medicine, and people do drink it.

115
00:13:49,284 --> 00:14:16,643
so uh here we have this whole business of really uh asking ourselves what we need what we actually need uh to sustain to sustain life so this is only the physical needs yeah i mean there's also the other side our cultural needs our heart needs and things like that in in the buddhist in the buddha's um instructions to the monks basically uh

116
00:14:17,315 --> 00:14:23,783
the day was to be spent meditating and remembering and studying and understanding the Dharma.

117
00:14:23,803 --> 00:14:28,149
So in those days, of course, you had to memorize the teaching, yeah?

118
00:14:28,791 --> 00:14:36,561
You know, they didn't have clever little gadgets like we've got to remember things.

119
00:14:38,683 --> 00:14:44,351
So one exercise, you know, you can just set yourself is to live one day, one day,

120
00:14:44,585 --> 00:14:47,269
with just what you need and just find out for yourself.

121
00:14:52,639 --> 00:14:58,532
The second one is more to do with just lifting the level of it to sufficiency.

122
00:14:59,013 --> 00:15:01,277
And that depends upon, I think, a lot on

123
00:15:01,813 --> 00:15:20,379
on our culture for instance when it comes to clothes you know people need a set of clothes for work they need a set of clothes for leisure set of clothes for climbing mountains and things like that so it's not a case of uh you know making ourselves miserable

124
00:15:20,360 --> 00:15:49,876
uh but just being uh clear you know in ourselves as to what we actually need and i think that if you if you spend just one day with need um and i think that undermines a lot of the fear and anxiety that comes about with the loss of wealth no matter how much no matter how much or how little wealth you had to suddenly find yourself unemployed and on the dole which is pretty miserable

125
00:15:49,856 --> 00:15:54,543
And you just find you can live with it, at least at a physical level.

126
00:15:57,785 --> 00:15:59,828
And then, of course, there's a final one of greed.

127
00:15:59,869 --> 00:16:02,893
Well, that takes us to another step that does.

128
00:16:04,534 --> 00:16:07,217
So I think most of us know when we're being greedy.

129
00:16:07,658 --> 00:16:10,802
I don't think I need to go into that too much.

130
00:16:11,726 --> 00:16:15,113
So, a couple of exercises there.

131
00:16:15,133 --> 00:16:29,157
When it comes to food, you know, just to have one day with what you feel is the cheapest and most sustainable food that you could have, that was good for the body.

132
00:16:30,419 --> 00:16:33,244
Just one day a week, you know, just to remind ourselves.

133
00:16:35,048 --> 00:16:35,168
Yeah.

134
00:16:35,187 --> 00:16:35,288
Yeah.

135
00:16:36,279 --> 00:16:42,246
And when it comes to clothes, just go through the wardrobe and just see how much of clothes you're not wearing.

136
00:16:42,967 --> 00:16:57,644
I remember somebody was in the habit of, in their wardrobe, if they used a piece from it, a shirt or some sort of dress, they would put it at one end.

137
00:16:58,446 --> 00:17:04,633
And then over the year, they would see all the clothes they hadn't actually used and they would take them down to the charity shop.

138
00:17:06,807 --> 00:17:13,835
So there's all sorts of little tricks that we can play on ourselves in order to actually, you know, just come down to sufficiency.

139
00:17:14,316 --> 00:17:16,278
And eventually it saves a lot of money, you know.

140
00:17:17,440 --> 00:17:21,443
When it comes to heating, you know, that's really quite crucial for us these days.

141
00:17:22,144 --> 00:17:25,269
And our heating bill is going to go up something awful.

142
00:17:25,348 --> 00:17:36,122
But just by, you know, being careful with it and wearing jumpers, you know, it won't be that heavy on us, I don't think.

143
00:17:38,211 --> 00:17:38,813
Very good.

144
00:17:38,853 --> 00:18:00,455
So, I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused any confusion, and that by your devotion to practice and the practice of poverty, simplicity, that's the word, simplicity, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

